Accidental Gollum Cosplay (Alopecia, and how I lost all my hair in 2 months)

images.description: Right before Christmas I noticed a small bald spot on my head. I didn’t think much of it- maybe I pulled a bunch of my hair out in the night, who knows? It would be fine I convinced myself...
Well, this little spot grew a bit bigger, and I started to get worried. But I could hide it, so as long as it didn’t get any bigger it would be a-ok, right? (Hair was wet, not greasy haha)

Well apparently my body wanted to cuss around with me because it kept growing, and growing. It was getting harder to hide and I because very self conscious. Being a woman in my mid twenties and having a now large bald spot on the side of my head was messing with my self image, and emotions. I went to see my doctor and she told me that I had an auto immune disease called alopecia areata. This meant that my body thought that my hair follicles were a foreign body and it was attacking it like a germ. Small patches of hair fall out. But not all hope was lost! Most people that develop this have a high chance of growing their hair back, though spots will continue to pop up every once in a while.

data.title: Joe Medicine Crow, the last known account of a Native American counting coup in war. Story Below

images.description:
Joe Medicine Crow was born on the Crow Reservation in 1913. His Step-Grandfather was called "White Man Runs Him" and was a scout for General George A. Custer and witnessed the Battle of the Little Bighorn in 1876.
in 1939, Joe was the first member of the Crow nation to achieve a Masters Degree which he got in  Anthropology from USC. He was working towards his Ph.D and completed the required coursework but halted because of the US involvement in WW2. He taught for a year in 1941 then took a defense industry job at the Bremerton, WA shipyards in 1942.

Counting Coup:
Counting coup was the winning of prestige against an enemy by the Plains Indians of North America. Warriors won prestige by acts of bravery in the face of the enemy, which could be recorded in various ways and retold as stories. Any blow struck against the enemy counted as a coup, but the most prestigious acts included touching an enemy warrior with the hand, bow, or coup stick and escaping unharmed. Touching the first enemy to die in battle or touching the enemy's defensive works also counted as coup.
Escaping unharmed while counting coup was considered a higher honor than being wounded in the attempt. A warrior who won coup was permitted to wear an eagle feather in his hair. If he had been wounded in the attempt, however, he was required to paint the feather red to indicate this

After a battle or exploit, the people of a tribe would gather together to recount their acts of bravery and "count coup." Coups were recorded by putting notches in a coup stick.[1] Indians of the Pacific Northwest would tie an eagle feather to their coup stick for each coup counted, but many tribes did not do so.

Joe's WW2 Coup Count:

After spending the latter half of 1942 working in the naval ship yards in Bremerton, Washington, Medicine Crow joined the Army in 1943. He became a scout in the 103rd Infantry Division, and fought in World War II. Whenever he went into battle, he wore his war paint (two red stripes on his arms) beneath his uniform and a sacred yellow painted eagle feather, provided by a "sundance" medicine man, beneath his helmet.

Joe completed all four tasks required to become a war chief: touching an enemy without killing him, taking an enemy's weapon, leading a successful war party, and stealing an enemy's horse. He touched a living enemy soldier and disarmed him after turning a corner and finding himself face to face with a young German soldier: "The collision knocked the German's weapon to the ground. Mr. Crow lowered his own weapon and the two fought hand-to-hand. In the end Mr. Crow got the best of the German, grabbing him by the neck and choking him. He was going to kill the German soldier on the spot when the man screamed out 'momma.' Mr. Crow then let him go"

He also led a successful war party and stole fifty horses owned by the Nazi SS from a German camp singing a traditional Crow honor song as he rode off.

Medicine Crow is the last member of the Crow tribe to become a war chief. He was interviewed and appeared in the 2007 Ken Burns PBS series The War, describing his World War II service. Filmmaker Ken Burns said, "The story of Joseph Medicine Crow is something I've wanted to tell for 20 years."

Unfortunate Shit Post
data.description:
I was watching re-runs of Ink Master today when I started to get a sour stomach. I was able to push out a few foul-smelling bombs, but it was becoming increasingly apparent that something much worse was on it's way. I'm usually pretty adept at determining whether it will be solid or gas, but today I believe I gambled a bit too long.

I was wearing socks, which is unusual for me in the house. I get better traction bare-footed. But it's February still, and my house gets drafty. I had another urge to expel gas, but this one was deceptive... You know, the feeling where you are beginning to pass gas, but then you feel a "thump" of solid hitting a wall and you know you're in trouble. So I shot up from the couch and scrambled up the stairs to my bathroom to relieve this "unstoppable force." (+1 to anyone who gets the reference)

3/4 of the way up the stairs, due to the effort I was exerting to climb them so frantically, I let out a wet FRAAAAP which caught me by surprise. My socked foot slipped on the next carpeted step, causing me to fall forward, hit my head on the top step, and then ungracefully slide down the stairs, hitting my chin numerous times. Finally, at the bottom, I rolled a bit, gasping, crying, and laughing all at once. And then it happened. I shit my pants.

Holy Shit FP. Hi! uhhhh...

1) I'm a chick
2) Bad Luck Brian would have been better, yes
3) No, I'm not going to take a picture of my shit, but I think there are websites out there for you....
4) Send pet pics. Love you all
